  "text": "what happened in the sutdy area (appendix), other researches, such as offshore of Oregon [CITATION_1] , show that the upward shift of the BHSZ may be true at the places other than high-latitude zones. The thinning of the HSZ caused dissociation of the hydrate located at the BHSZ. The buoyancy of the released gas would have generated excess pore pressure that could have led to the development of hydraulic fractures [CITATION_2] . Therefore, the gas chimneys are interpreted to form during the period of rapid shallowing of the BHSZ, though the accurate timing of this formation is hard to determine. The hydrate started to accrete after the gas conduit was established between the sediments below the BHSZ and at the level of reflections D and E. Since then the hydrate accretion would continue as the BHSZ shoaled (Fig. 5) . It is unlikely but cannot be ruled out entirely that the spatial relationship between the gas chimneys and the BSR is coincident.",
